P. 86,1. 28. ignis . . . infusione. These words are difficult to translate and explain, and are possibly the result of a note subsequently incorporated in the text. They are intended to make clear the process described above in the words ‘importunis estua- tionibus vexet illud atque consumat,' and the first part of the passage, ‘ igniS scilicet ex estuatione‚' only repeats those words in a slightly different form. The difficulty is in the words ‘plumbi infusione? Probably they had not much more meaning for the author than they have for us. He admits (infra, I. vi. K) that he knew little about the process of assaying, and he may have merely wished to indicate in a vague way that lead was used in it. The ways in which silver might be lost in an assay cannot all be included under the two heads here given. Professor H. Louis, who has been good enough to consider this question for us, suggests that the words ‘ plumbi infusione ' refer to the portion of the process called by the Gerrnans ‘eintranken‚' i. e. the melting of the silver in the bath of molten lead. The passage is alluded to in one of the appendices to the treatise ‘De Moneta' in the Red Book of the Exchequer (Red Book, p. 1006), and is there paraphrased ‘ vel propter nimiam estuationem vel alzl‘er} showing that the fourteenth-century assayer who wrote the note did not understand ‘ plumbi infusione.'
